A question we should never ask ourselves ever: Given we can work with complex matrices \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {C}), but we often find ourselves in many applications caring about rational matrices \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {Q}). For example if we have two matrices A,B\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {Q}) we see that A,B\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {C}), so is asking:
Is A\sim _{\mathbb {Q}}B, i.e., is there an invertible X\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {Q}) such that A=XBX^{-1}?
Is this the same as asking,
Is A\sim _{\mathbb {C}}B, i.e., is there an invertible X\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}
olimits _{n}(\mathbb {C}) such that A=XBX^{-1}?
or not?
